      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="gpp_data"><a class="gpp_link" href="https://plus.google.com/112788519324230096635?rel=author">Edward Lathrop</a> <br /><span class="gpp_bio">Webmaster and Administrator of, as well as contributor to <a href="http://stopanxietystoppanic.com">Stop Anxiety Stop Panic</a>.</span></div><p>When <a href="http://www.stopanxietystoppanic.com/anxiety_disorder/coping-with-anxiety/" >coping with anxiety</a>, even an anxiety disorder that is accompanied with <a href="http://www.stopanxietystoppanic.com/today" >panic attacks</a>, it is important to learn that anxiety thrives when you are most apprehensive it will strike. In other words, if you were in a state of mind anxiety would not upset you or would not discomfort for you in any way, and furthermore you were not at all put off or taken back by <a href="http://www.stopanxietystoppanic.com/today" >panic attacks</a>, anxiety and panic would never strike.</p>
<div id="attachment_986" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 293px"><a href="http://www.stopanxietystoppanic.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Taking-Time-to-Relax.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-986" title="Taking Time to Relax" src="http://www.stopanxietystoppanic.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Taking-Time-to-Relax.jpg" alt="Taking Time For Yourself" width="283" height="424" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Take Time For Relaxing</p></div>
<p>Certainly anxiety disorder is a condition that no one tries to manifest. It would not be natural for someone to want to experience panic attacks or even slightly discomforting spells of anxiety. Still, it is when our apprehension of these things puts us on high alert that we lay the groundwork for anxiety to enter into our lives and <a href="http://www.stopanxietystoppanic.com/today" >panic attack</a> to overwhelm us.</p>
<p>Of course, no one can recommend actually enjoying anxiety and panic. However, it is when we have a mindset that makes us center our lives on trying to fight anxiety away and brace ourselves for panic attacks, we make our lives more prone to experiencing them.</p>
<p>The opposite of fighting anxiety and bracing ourselves for panic attacks is relaxation. When we take a relaxed attitude that panic and anxiety may just happen and we will be none the worse if they do, that we make ourselves less inviting to panic and anxiety. In other words, we are better able to be relaxed when we are not in constant fear of what will happen next. Also, we will not be in constant fear of panic and anxiety when we realize they will do us no more harm than they already have in the past.</p>
<p>Learning to physically relax helps us to take a more relaxed attitude. This is true whether we are trying to relax our attitudes toward anxiety so we can better cope with it, or if we were are trying to relax to simply help ourselves get more enjoyment out of life. The important thing to realize is that physical relaxation exercises help us to mentally relax our attitudes. Therefore, it is wise we make a daily practice of at least a half-hour of practicing physical relaxation.</p>
<p>Physical relaxation exercising can be as simple as laying down, closing your eyes, breathing a little  more deeply and slowly than normal and feeling the muscle groups in your body become less tense. The relaxation experience is further enhanced if, once we bring ourselves into a relaxed state, we concentrate on facing every day as a very relaxed person, being un-bothered by anything that happens throughout our day.</p>
<p>For hundreds of years it has been known that people who take brief respites were they can be relaxed are people who are better able to cope with anxiety and are less prone to having panic attacks.</p>
