&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;a type="audio/mpeg" href="http://podcasts.odiogo.com/get_mp3.mp3?f=/stop-anxiety-stop-panic/Stop_Anxiety_Stop_Panic-Panic_Attack_Symptoms.mp3"&gt;Click here to play&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;</description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="gpp_data"><a class="gpp_link" href="https://plus.google.com/112788519324230096635?rel=author">Edward Lathrop</a> <br /><span class="gpp_bio">Webmaster and Administrator of, as well as contributor to <a href="http://stopanxietystoppanic.com">Stop Anxiety Stop Panic</a>.</span></div><p><em> by Melisa Gerrow</em></p>
<div id="attachment_972" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 251px"><a href="http://www.stopanxietystoppanic.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/REPAY_STUDENT_LOAN32.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-972" src="http://www.stopanxietystoppanic.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/REPAY_STUDENT_LOAN32.jpg" alt="Unreal feelings" width="241" height="325" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Feeling Like Everything is Unreal</p></div>
<p>A <a href="http://www.stopanxietystoppanic.com/today" >panic attack</a> symptom is any symptom of any type of illness or physical calamity that is felt due to a state of anxiety instead of having a true underlying cause. Some of these &#8220;fake&#8221; symptoms can be mocked symptoms of a very disastrous physical occurrence, such as having a heart attack or thinking a stroke may be occurring.</p>
<p>Let me say this right off the bat; if you have any reason to suspect you may be having some serious affliction, such as a heart attack or a stroke, seek medical attention, immediately. Do not take a chance it may be a <a href="http://www.stopanxietystoppanic.com/today" >panic attack</a> causing these symptoms. Before you conclude it is panic causing such symptoms, make sure your doctor tells you it is!</p>
<p>Having said that, it is very common for a person to think he or she is having some serious physical problem when it is panic attack fooling him/her into believing it is. Very often, panic will make a person feel as if he or she is short of breath or dizzy, when in fact it is an overabundance of adrenaline pumping through the bloodstream that is making him/her feel this way.</p>
<p>Panic can bring all sorts of symptoms. Sometimes people feel as if they have what is described as a feeling of un-realness. They claim they feel as if they are in another world and everything they see appears as if it is on an old film. They cannot connect with the world and, as one woman described it; &#8220;I feel totally out of it!&#8221;</p>
<p>Such feelings make people believe they are having some sort of a mental breakdown. Actually, panic is not mental; <a href="http://www.stopanxietystoppanic.com/today" >panic attacks</a> are physical conditions. There brought on by an abundance of stress which multiplies into an anxiety disorder and this anxiety disorder keeps them in a state where adrenaline is flowing inordinately at all times. It is adrenaline that is responsible for these feelings of un-realness.</p>
<p>It is learning how to stop adrenaline from flowing over abundantly and at inappropriate times that is the key to <a href="http://www.stopanxietystoppanic.com/today"  rel='nofollow' >stopping panic</a> attack symptoms. There is no part of the brain that can fail and make a person have a panic attack. At times, it can be beneficial to receive psychiatric help because this can uncover what the underlying cause of the anxiety is.</p>
<p>However, many times self-help techniques can be very beneficial in <a href="http://www.stopanxietystoppanic.com/today"  rel='nofollow' >overcoming anxiety</a> and panic. Such self help techniques include learning what causes <a href="http://www.stopanxietystoppanic.com/today" >panic attacks</a>, how to better deal with stress and how to stop adrenaline from building to the point it causes one to feel symptoms of panic attacks.</p>
